## Key Guidance for Families

**Start with QMB.** It offers the most comprehensive coverage. If income is too high, move to SLMB, then QI-1.[1][7]

**Income limits matter most.** For 2026, a single person in Illinois can earn up to $1,330/month for QMB, $1,596/month for SLMB.[4] These thresholds reset every April, so annual recertification is essential.[1][4]

**Asset limits are strict.** An individual can have no more than $9,950 in countable assets; couples, $14,910.[4] However, the search results do not specify which assets count (home equity, vehicles, retirement accounts) or which are exempt—families should ask their caseworker for clarification.

**Application lag matters.** QMB premiums take effect the month *after* approval, not the approval month itself.[4] SLMB offers a small advantage: Part B premiums can be backdated up to 3 months.[4]

**QI-1 is limited.** Only a fixed number of spots are available each year, awarded first-come, first-served.[7] It's not a guaranteed benefit.

**Contact the DHS Helpline** at **1-800-843-6154** (Monday–Friday, 8:30 a.m.–5:00 p.m., except state holidays) or visit your local Family Community Resource Center in person to apply.[1]

